Evaluation of Zika virus research collaboration

Mateo Reveiz

Zika is an infectious disease caused by the Zika virus. The virus is mostly transmitted through the Aedes species mosquito (Ae. aegypti and Ae. albopictus). It can also be transmitted through a pregnant woman to a fetus and through sexual activity.

Although Zika's mortality rate is fairly low, and most people might not even realize they have Zika, it is still dangerous for pregnant women and a developing fetus. Indeed, Zika infection during pregnancy can cause birth defects of the brain (microcephaly). Additionally, there have been increased reports of Guillain-Barr syndrome in areas affected by Zika.

More information about Zika can be found in the CDC website, as well as the Pan American Health Organization (Paho).

In 2016, the WHO declared the Zika virus outbreak an international public health emergency. The poorly researched topic suddenly became a focal investigation point among many countries. The global response to this outbreak and the collaboration that emerged between countries is essential to understand regional interactions that could be reinforced for future outbreaks.

This analysis will try to investigate the collaboration between countries from two main sources. First, we will focus on the reported affiliation from the authors of each article. Once country affiliations are identified and analysed, we will focus on the actual content of the articles by analyzing the abstracts. The goal of this second analysis is o identify key reseach areas and how countries might speciliaze or prioritize certain areas above others.

We will start by inclusing some libraries for our analysis

Although this analysis does not take into consideration the language of the country, it would be interesting to also add that variable in the future.

All the information was downloaded from http://www.geonames.org/ and saved as a text file.

"zika virus"[MeSH Terms] OR ("zika"[All Fields] AND "virus"[All Fields]) OR "zika virus"[All Fields] OR "zika"[All Fields] OR "zika virus infection"[MeSH Terms] OR ("zika"[All Fields] AND "virus"[All Fields] AND "infection"[All Fields]) OR "zika virus infection"[All Fields]

Before we actually parse the XML data, we will define multiple helper functions

First we have a function that recursively extracts the text from a given XML node.

In [5]:
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4485132/python-how-do-you-get-an-xml-elements-text-content-using-xml-dom-minidom
# mike rodent, answered May 16 '15 at 12:02
# Recursively get all text from a node
def get_all_text(node):
        if node.nodeType ==  node.TEXT_NODE:
            return node.data.strip()
        else:
            text_string = " "
            for child_node in node.childNodes:
                text_string += get_all_text(child_node)
            return text_string.strip()

For certain affiliations, we need to handle specific cases that are not detected well by the GeoText module imported. Although this list is very short, it can be expanded in the future to ensure more accurate geographical data.

In [6]:
# Sometimes some countries, states, cities of particular importance have to be handled as special cases
# For this assignment, this list is very limited. However, over time, this should be refined
def handle_special_case(countries):
    for country in countries:
        if country == "Georgia":
            return True, "United States"
    return False, ""

Affiliations can have this form:

"Centro de Estudios Parasitolgicos y de Vectores (CEPAVE-CONICET), Universidad Nacional de La Plata, La Plata, Buenos Aires, Argentina."

From this, the country "Argentina" is detected as well as the cities La Plata and Buenos Aires. Those two cities appear in two countries, Colombia and Argentina. A higher weight is given to direct country mentions although city mentions do have some weight. At the end, this affiliation is classified as Argentina. ['Argentina'] [('Argentina', 2), ('Colombia', 2)] -> Argentina

The results from this program use the geotext module for country detection and give decent results. However, it is necessary to improve the accuracy of the program to avoid country misclassifications.

In [7]:
# countries: list of strings ['United States']
# countries_mentions list of tuples [('United States', 2), ('Australia', 1)]
# Given this, we need to make the best guess as to what the country really is
# This is a helper method for get_affiliations() below
def country_decider(countries, countries_mentions):
    ret = defaultdict(int)    
    
    # If no affiliations detected, return nan
    if len(countries) == 0 and countries_mentions == 0:
        return np.nan
    
    # If special case, return
    flag, final_country = handle_special_case(countries)
    if flag:
        return final_country
        
    for country in countries:
        ret[country] += 2 # give higher weight to country label
        
    for country, mentions in countries_mentions:
        ret[country] += mentions
        
    max_m = 0
    final_country = np.nan
    for k,v in ret.items():
        if v > max_m:
            max_m = v
            final_country = k
    
    return final_country

Getting the abstract is pretty straightforward:

In [8]:
# Extracts an article's abstract
def get_abstract(article):
    abstract_nodes = article.getElementsByTagName("Abstract")
    abstract = " ".join(get_all_text(t) for t in abstract_nodes)
    return abstract

Dates are converted from strings to datetime objects. When no date is found, a hot-deck imputation method is used as the articles were downloaded in chronological order. It is worth noting that the publication date that we extract differs from the actual moment an article is written, sent for approval, or approved. Therefore, we might see some articles whose dates are in the "future" or 2020.

In [ ]:
# Extracts an article's date, converts it to datetime object
def get_date(article, last_date):
    date_node = article.getElementsByTagName("PubMedPubDate")    
    
    # Hot-deck imputation if date is missing
    date = last_date
    
    # Not all articles might have date
    if len(date_node) > 0:
        year_node = date_node[0].getElementsByTagName("Year")
        month_node = date_node[0].getElementsByTagName("Month")
        day_node = date_node[0].getElementsByTagName("Day")
    
        # Sometimes the day or month might be missing
        if len(year_node) > 0 and len(month_node) > 0 and len(day_node) > 0:    
            dateY = year_node[0].childNodes[0].data
            dateM = month_node[0].childNodes[0].data
            dateD = day_node[0].childNodes[0].data
            date = datetime.strptime("{}/{}/{}".format(dateY, dateM, dateD), "%Y/%m/%d")
            last_date = date
     
        
    return date, last_date

Getting the title is pretty straightforward as well. Although we will not use this information for the moment in the analysis, it is certainly useful to keep for future updates of this code.

In [10]:
# Extracts an article's title
def get_title(article):
    # Extract article title. When <i>title</i> or <sup>title</sup> are used, we need to enter the child and concatenate
    # by recursively extracting text from nodes
    title_node = article.getElementsByTagName("ArticleTitle")[0].childNodes 
    title = " ".join(get_all_text(t) for t in title_node)  
    return title

This is the main affiliation getter, which calls other helper methods above.

In [11]:
def get_affiliations(article):
    affil_node = article.getElementsByTagName("Affiliation")      
    # Each article has multiple authors, multiple affiliations
    article_affiliations = defaultdict(int)
    for affil in affil_node:
        # Get text
        affil_text = affil.firstChild.data
        
        # Find mentions from cities, countries etc..
        cities = GeoText(affil_text).cities
        countries_mentions = GeoText(affil_text).country_mentions
        countries = GeoText(affil_text).countries   
        
        # Handle special cases not detected
        my_regex = r"\bUK\b"
        if re.search(my_regex, affil_text, flags=re.IGNORECASE):
            countries.append("United Kingdom")
            countries.append("United Kingdom")
        
        # countries_mentions gives country code and mention name as a dictionary
        # extract key/value pair and transorm code to full country name        
        countries_mentions  = [(df_countries.loc[df_countries["Code"] == k]["Country"].values[0],v) for k,v in countries_mentions.items()]         
                        
        # Get majority vote on country
        final_country = country_decider(countries, countries_mentions)    
                        
        # Add mentions to overall article unless nan
        if not pd.isnull(final_country):
            article_affiliations[final_country] += 1 
            # Add mentions to table
            df_countries.loc[final_country, "total_occur"] += 1
            
    
    if len(article_affiliations) == 0:
        article_affiliations = np.nan
    else:   
        for k,v in article_affiliations.items():            
            df_countries.loc[k, "uniq_occur"] += 1  
            
    return article_affiliations

The last helper method is the keyword getter. We are done with helper methods!

In [12]:
# Extract keywords
def get_keywords(article):
    keyword_nodes = article.getElementsByTagName("Keyword")
    keywords = []    
    [keywords.append(get_all_text(t).lower()) for t in keyword_nodes]  
    
    return keywords

After defining all those helper methods, we can finally go through the data and parse the information. For each article, we extract titles, dates, keywords, abstracts and affiliations and save them to the corresponding tables.

In [13]:
# Hot deck imputation if the date is missing. (Pubmed articles were downloaded by chronologcal sorting)
last_date = 0
offset = 0

no_affil_count = 0
no_keyword_count = 0

for i, article in enumerate(articles): 
     
    # Extract title
    title = get_title(article)        
    
    # Extract date    
    date, last_date = get_date(article, last_date) 
    
    # Extract abstract    
    abstract = get_abstract(article)  
        
    # Extract affiliations
    affiliations = get_affiliations(article)  
    
    # Extract keywords
    keywords = get_keywords(article)
    
    # Skip if no affiliations
    if pd.isnull(affiliations):
        offset = offset + 1
        no_affil_count = no_affil_count + 1
        continue
    
    # Add to articles table
    df_articles.at[i-offset, "articleID"] = i - offset   # This should continous numbering, if skipped have to handle later TODO
    df_articles.at[i-offset, "title"] = title
    df_articles.at[i-offset, "date"] = date
    df_articles.at[i-offset, "abstract"] = abstract
    
    # Add to article article_countries table    
    for country,mentions in affiliations.items():        
        continent=df_countries.loc[df_countries["Country"]==country]["Continent"].values[0]
        df_article_countries.loc[len(df_article_countries)]=[i-offset, country, mentions, continent] 
        
    #Add to article_keywords table
    if len(keywords) == 0:
        no_keyword_count = no_keyword_count + 1
        df_article_keywords.loc[len(df_article_keywords)]=[i-offset, np.nan]
        df_articles.at[i-offset, "all_keywords"] = ""
    else:
        all_keywords = " ".join(keywords)
        df_articles.at[i-offset, "all_keywords"] = all_keywords
        for keyword in keywords:
            df_article_keywords.loc[len(df_article_keywords)]=[i-offset, keyword.lower().replace("", "e")]

Part 2: Clustering from affiliation information

The first and main part of the analysis relies on affilaition information. In this section, we want to understand how countries collaborate with each other by writing articles together.

First, we can look at the number of articles published for each continent.

Most of the research is conducted by North America and Europe. South America (the focus of the Zika outbreak) has a decent research output comparable to Asia. Africa and Oceania have very small contributions. In further analsysi this could be compared to other diseases to understand if this research is specific to Zika or not. Now let's take a closer look at specific countries.

From this, we can see that most articles have a single country affiliation (66%). The rest of the distribution decreases monotonically for the number of affiliations, with up to 21 countries involved in a single article. At this point, it is worth noting the scale at which we are analysing this dataset. The "country" scale was chosen becacuse it is easier to categorize affiliations this way and also represents a good compromise between local efforts and global initiatives. However, within each category, it is important to recognize the inner collaboration within a country at a state, local or intitutional level.

That being said, we can expand this this general trend and apply it to the top countries.

top_countries = df_countries.loc[df_countries["uniq_occur"] > 1].sort_values(by=['uniq_occur'], ascending=False)["Country"]

all_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=["country", "country_mentions", "continent", "curr_country"])
for top_cont in top_countries[0:10]:
    # Indeces for specific country
    indeces = df_article_countries.loc[df_article_countries["country"] == top_cont]["articleID"].values
    # Make counts for number of countries shared by article
    df=df_article_countries.loc[df_article_countries["articleID"].isin(indeces)].groupby("articleID").count().groupby(["country"]).count().reset_index()
    # Get total number of articles
    total_articles = df["country_mentions"].sum()
    # Normalize as percentage
    df["country_mentions"]=df["country_mentions"]/total_articles*100
    # Add current country
    df["curr_country"] = top_cont
    # Add data to overall table
    all_data=pd.concat([all_data, df[0:9]])

The United States and Brazil are the only countries among the top 10 that have more than 50% of their research being conducted without external collaboration. There seems to be a correlation between total number of articles pusblished and number of country collaborators.

On the other side, European countries such as the UK, Germany and France have the lowest, individually conducted reseach suggesting higher collaboration. These 3 countries have more than 65% of their research shared by other countries.

We can plot the total number of articles written by a country (x-axis) versus the number of articles written with i other countries affiliated. We should expect a linear relationship between these two. However, deviations from the model will suggest higher or lower collaboration rates with other countries.

In [189]:
all_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=["country", "country_mentions", "continent", "curr_country"])
for top_cont in top_countries:
    # Indeces for specific country
    indeces = df_article_countries.loc[df_article_countries["country"] == top_cont]["articleID"].values
    # Make counts for number of countries shared by article
    df=df_article_countries.loc[df_article_countries["articleID"].isin(indeces)].groupby("articleID").count().groupby(["country"]).count().reset_index()
    # Get total number of articles
    total_articles = df["country_mentions"].sum()
    # Normalize as percentage
    df["country_mentions"]=df["country_mentions"]
    # Add current country
    df["curr_country"] = top_cont
    # Add data to overall table
    all_data=pd.concat([all_data, df[0:9]])
    
print("Model: number articles shared with i collaborators ~ total number of articles")
print("Residual = y_real - y_model", "\n")

for i in [1,2,3,4]:
    plt.subplot(8,2,i*2-1)
    df=df_countries.sort_values(by=['uniq_occur'], ascending=False)[["uniq_occur", "Country"]]
    df=df.merge(all_data.loc[all_data["country"]==i], left_on="Country", right_on="curr_country")   
    
    # Plot data and fitted model
    sns.scatterplot(x="uniq_occur", y="country_mentions", data=df, legend=False)
    fit_coef = np.polyfit(df["uniq_occur"].values, df["country_mentions"].values.astype(np.int64), 1)
    x_fit = np.linspace(0, 2600, 100)
    y_fit = np.poly1d(fit_coef)(x_fit)
    plt.plot(x_fit,y_fit, 'r-')
    plt.xlabel("Total articles")
    plt.ylabel("Articles with {} country aff.".format(i))
    plt.title("Articles with {} country affiliations vs total number of articles".format(i))
    
    
    # Get residuals, exceptions
    df["resid"] = df["country_mentions"] - np.poly1d(fit_coef)(df["uniq_occur"])    
    exceptions=df.loc[np.abs(df["resid"]) > df["resid"].std() * 1.5]    
    print("Countries with residuals > 1.5 standard deviations ({}) for {} country affiliations".format(round(df["resid"].std() * 1.5), i))
    print(exceptions[["Country", "uniq_occur", "country_mentions", "resid"]], "\n\n") 
    
    # Plot residuals
    plt.subplot(8,2,i*2)
    sns.scatterplot(x="uniq_occur", y="resid", data=df, legend=False) 
    plt.subplots_adjust(top = 1.2, hspace = 0.5)
    plt.xlabel("Total articles")
    plt.ylabel("Residual with {} country ".format(i))
    plt.title("Residuals")
    
    # Add labels to exceptions on residuals
    for j in range(0,len(exceptions["uniq_occur"])):

This fit has residuals centered around 0 and a certain degree of homoscedasticity which breaks with certain outliers. These outliers defiend as countries 1.5 times the standard deviation away give us some insight. First of all, the outliers tend to have the highest research output overall (U.S, UK, France and China). Brazil (for the most part), Italy and India are exceptions as they are not considered outliers. This means that they do follow the collaboration model fairly well. For the first row of graphs (1 affiliation or 0 collaborating countries), the U.S has the highest positive deviation which implies that the U.S. produces more 1-affiliation (no collaboration) articles than the expected model. The European countries and Thailand have the highest negative residuals suggesting lower 1-affiliation articles than predicted.

The residual sign changes as expected for 2,3,4-affiliation in the articles. Indeed, The U.S now produces less shared articles in all those categories than most of the other European countries. Overall, European countries have the tendency to produce more collaborative articles as previously expected.

Graph representation

Now that we have an idea about what countries collaborate the most, we want to understand who they actually work with. In order to do create a graphical representation of collaboration, we will start by making a bipartite graph. One set of nodes will contain countries and the other set of nodes will represent articles. In order to create edges, unique affiliations will be considered. For example let's say article A has 3 authors from the U.S., 2 authors from France and 1 from Brazil. Therefore, an node A wil be connected to the U.S, France and Brazil, with a weight of 1 for each. The multiplicity of authors from a same country for a given article is therefore discarded. This weighing method is chosen to reduce saturation effects.

In [27]:
# Create graph
g = nx.Graph()

# Get countries with at least one article, add nodes to graph
countries = df_countries.loc[df_countries["uniq_occur"] > 0]["Country"]
for country in countries:
    g.add_node(country)
    n = g.node[country]    
    n["Maincountry"] = True
    n["start_time"] = "1967/01/01"
    n["end_time"] = "2021/01/01"
    n["end_time_int"] = "2021/01/01"

# Loop through articles, add them to the graph
articleIDs = df_article_countries["articleID"]
for id_a in articleIDs.unique():
    g.add_node(id_a)
    n = g.node[id_a]    
    n["Maincountry"] = False
    date = df_articles.loc[df_articles["articleID"] == id_a]["date"].values[0]
    n["start_time"] = date.strftime('%Y/%m/%d')
    n["end_time_int"] = (date + timedelta(weeks=8)).strftime('%Y/%m/%d')
    n["end_time"] = "2021/01/01"
    
# Connect articles to the countries they are affiliated to
countries = df_article_countries["country"]
for a_id,country in zip(articleIDs, countries):
    g.add_edge(a_id, country)   

# Save graph file to export to another visualization program (gephi)   
nx.write_gexf(g, "zika_2.gexf")

This builds a bipartite graph with nodes being either countries (green) or articles (pink). Labels and node size are proportional to the node degree. Only countries with more than 11 articles are being labeled for clarity reasons in the graph. All other countries are still displayed without the label.

We can also perform a community detection algorithm. A resolution of 2.2 was chosen to obtain 6 clusters.

This was achieved through Gephi, by using the algorithm described by:

Vincent D Blondel, Jean-Loup Guillaume, Renaud Lambiotte, Etienne Lefebvre, Fast unfolding of communities in large networks, in Journal of Statistical Mechanics: Theory and Experiment 2008 (10), P1000

From visual inspection, communities seem to overlap with grographical information. For example, most European countries work together as a tight community (green). South american countries tend to work together as well as Spain (purple). This is likely due to same use of language (Spanish). Asian countries have a more disperesed collaboration with no clear, tight communities. China, Thailand, Hong Kong and South Korea share a community (brown) while India, Pakistan, Malaysia, Vietnam are in another (dark purple).

As this graph is difficult to study, we can take a closer look at individual communities on their own. We will only display The largest cluster (green), and clusters containing the largest research-producing countries (Brazil, United States, China). The South American cluster is also displayed as Zika ostly influenced this region.

These communities show once again the strong collaboration in European countries, compared to all other regions. However, decomposing the clusters into different connected components can be misleading. For example, Brazil and the United States do have a very large number of shared articles. However, this strong association is not clear from the individual connected components as they are in different clusters.

It is necessary to focus on a limited subset of countries to obain more in depth collaboration metrics.

Describing collaboration for each country in this way allows us to expand the model. We can create a projection of the bipartite graph from this information that only contains country nodes and abstracts away the article nodes.

In order to do this, we will have a weight between country pairs that represents the number of articles in which bot countries appear.

Part 3: Clustering from abstract information

From the article affiliations, we have been able to cluster countries and create the collaboration graph. We now want to take advantage of the abstract and keyword information for each document. The abstract can give us an idea on the topics covered and research interests of the article.

However, due to the limited scope and time frame of this assignment and the complexity of the abstract information, we will focus on the keyword information which displays lower levels of noise and variance that require less complex NLP methods and topic-specifc knowledge in the research area. It is worth noting that keywords are missing in many articles as mentioned in the first part of the analysis and might not completly represent the entire dataset (about 50% of articles provide keywords). This again would be solved by using abstract and full document information in a future, more through analysis.

In [33]:
# Get abstract data for the articles
corpus=df_articles["all_keywords"].values # for an abstract analysis, simply replace "all_keywords" with "abstract"
corpus_ids = df_articles["articleID"].values

This simple NLP analysis uses a Snowball stemming in order to more easily capture very similar words into single entities. Punctuation is also removed.

Once the words are preprocessed, we calculate the tf-idf of the entire corpus. Ths step basically gives a weight to each word based onits frequency within a document whiile giving less weight to very common words that appear in many documents and therefore yield very low levels of information gain.

The tf-idf for the corpus serves to create an encoder that transforms documents into feature vectors. These vectors now define or serve as the signature of the document.

In [34]:
# Preprocess data (remove punctuation, numbers, put lowercase)
translator = str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)
corpus = [re.sub(r"\d", "", s.lower().translate(translator)) for s in corpus]

stemmer = SnowballStemmer('english')

def stem_tokens(tokens):
    stemmed_tokens = []
    for token in tokens:
        stemmed_tokens.append(stemmer.stem(token))
    return stemmed_tokens

def tokenize(doc):
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(doc)
    stemmed_tokens = stem_tokens(tokens)
    return stemmed_tokens

        
# Calculate tf-idf
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(tokenizer=tokenize)
tfs = vectorizer.fit(corpus)
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names()


# Write the vectors to a csv first as this is much faster than loading them one by one to
# a pandas table
with open("temp.csv", "w", newline='', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    wr = csv.writer(f, delimiter=",")
    wr.writerow(["articleID"] + feature_names)
    for i, (doc,id_) in enumerate(zip(corpus,corpus_ids)):        
        # i and id_ are most liekly the same (but if in future code changes rows are dropped and IDs are not continuous
        # it is better to have a robust link to the articleIDs
        vector = [id_] + list(vectorizer.transform([doc]).toarray()[0])
        wr.writerow(vector)
    
# Create table to store the feature vectors for all documents from csv
abstract_vectors = pd.read_csv("temp.csv")
  

# Transform pandas table into numpy array for kmeans. We ignore the articleID column 
dataset_array = abstract_vectors.loc[:, abstract_vectors.columns != 'articleID'].values

Now that each article has a feature vector (from the keywords), we can use k-means to cluster articles together. An individual article now has a cluster number assigned.

In [197]:

df_articles["kmeans_cluster"] = kmeans.predict(dataset_array)

Let's go through the clusters and display the top keywords. Note that we are displaying a table that was manually created from these keywords with the given code. This manual intervention is necessary to evaluate the clusters and attempt to assign some "meaning" or global key term to each cluster.

For each column, important keywords (bold) were used to get a general sense of the cluster (last row). This more subjective human work is essential and requires some specific knowledge in the area. Further collaboration with scientists could help improve the categorization of these keywords.

That being said, clusters 0 to 5 show strong coherent ideas. The first cluster evokes more biological type of work. The second mentions molecular ideas, drug development. Keyword ssuch as structure and design were not included as contextual information is missing but they could likely be related to drug design or molecular structure properties.

The third cluster is the only that mentions specific geographical regions, travel and public health issues related to outbreak management.

The fourth cluster emphasizes neurological and nervous system effects and diseases such as Guillain-Barre and microencephalia. These are related in practice to pregnant women and fetal syndromes, both of which appear as keywords as well.

The fifth cluster highlights transmission vectors and infection related terms such as mosquito species (Culex, Aed for Aedes Aegypty) as well as mosquito-specific bacteria (Wolbachia). Insecticids and control are also reported, which relate to mosquito control methods.

The last cluster exhibits more heterogenous behavior. However, there is some emphasis on immunological terms such as antivirus, antibodies, immunology, viral, infection and vaccine.

Note: Runnning this code multiple times (as well as the clustering method) will always yield differences between runs. This is due to the inherent randomness included in the k-means algorithm during initialization. Therefore, the cluster number will likely differ from the displayed manual overarching themes (cluster 0 might display cluster 5's information in some other run). A more robust identification method relying less and less on human intervention is out of the scope os this analysis but constitutes an important feature in the future.

After clustering articles we can group the documents by country to investigate new trends. We can expand this analysis by grouping the features for all countries. Indeed, we can define a new feature vector for each country as a histogram for each country containing the cluster distribution of its articles. Once each country has a feature vector, we can cluster again the countries to detemine country similarities and potential research focus similarities.

In [228]:
def get_country_vec(data):
    f = np.arange(0.0, NUM_CLUSTERS)
    for i in range(0,NUM_CLUSTERS):
        num=data.loc[data["kmeans_cluster"]==i]["title"].values        
        f[i] = num[0] if len(num) > 0 else 0
    return f

This is difficult to evaluate and interpret. We will go back to the document feature vectors and forget about countries for a moment. Let's remember that we calculated the entire similarity matrix between each article (that has keywords). We could use this as weights between nodes in a graph. However, if we care about clustering countries from the articles and not the articles themselves, we will create a new projection of the bipartite graph to the country set.

However, at this is a O(n^2) operation plus looping through many countries for each article takes time. We will instead randomly select 500 articles. This represents about 50% of the articles that contain keywords and about 10% of the total downloaded articles so take this part with a grain of salt! The actual construction from all articles using abstract or full document information would really be more valuable in this case. But for the sake of the method, let's build this graph:

We first sample 500 points (articles) which have keywords (we don't want to sample articles that don't even have a keayword list!).

In [273]:
# We only want to sample 500 aticles from the article that do have keywords

# Find indeces of articles with keywords
indeces=df_articles.loc[df_articles["all_keywords"]!=""]["articleID"].sample(n=500).values

# Get those articles
df=abstract_vectors.loc[abstract_vectors["articleID"].isin(indeces)]

# Recalculate indeces because isin() suffles them and we do care aboutthe final df articleID order
indeces = df["articleID"].values

# Remove articleID column from df
df=df.loc[:, df.columns != 'articleID']

# Calculate similarity between vectors, get matrix
similarity_matrix=cosine_similarity(df)

Now, the actual graph

In [274]:
# Create graph
g = nx.Graph()

# Get countries with at least one article, add nodes to graph
countries = df_countries.loc[df_countries["uniq_occur"] > 0]["Country"]
for country in countries:
    g.add_node(country)
    n = g.node[country] 
    n["Maincountry"] = True
    n["start_time"] = "1967/01/01"
    n["end_time"] = "2021/01/01"
    n["end_time_int"] = "2021/01/01"
    
num_articles = len(similarity_matrix)
    
# Loop through all articles that we selected (that have keywords)
for i in range(0, num_articles):
            
    # Get i articleID
    id_i = indeces[i]
    # Get countries from article i    
    countries_i = df_article_countries[df_article_countries["articleID"]==id_i]["country"].values  
    
    for j in range(i+1,num_articles):         
        # Get j articleID
        id_j = indeces[j]
        # Get countries from article j
        countries_j = df_article_countries[df_article_countries["articleID"]==id_j]["country"].values
        
        # Num countries between both article affiliations to normalize
        num_countries = len(np.unique(np.concatenate((countries_i, countries_j))))
        
        # Get similarity between articles i and j, use as weight and use hyperbolic normalization 
        weight_ij = similarity_matrix[i][j] / num_countries
                
        # Connect nodes        
        for c1 in countries_i:
            for c2 in countries_j:
                if c1 != c2:                    
                    w = g.get_edge_data(c1,c2, default={"weight":0})["weight"]                     
                    g.add_edge(c1, c2, weight= w + weight_ij)
        
        
nx.write_gexf(g, "zika_tfidf.gexf")
